Thursday, June 21, 2007
Guilty plea in Dr. Seuss thefts
BY KIMBALL PERRY | KPERRY@ENQUIRER.COM
It's off to the slam, I am, because I'm in a jam, I am.

That's what John Hunnicutt is trying to avoid.

Hunnicutt pleaded guilty to the theft of more than $50,000 in autographed
Dr. Seuss lithographs and jade figurines stolen from Kathleen Lester's
Symmes Township home.

Now he's cooperating with police, hoping to lessen his prison sentence.

That led to the Tuesday arrest and Wednesday court appearance of Sean
Kammerer.

Hunnicutt, 41, pleaded guilty June 14 to burglarizing Lester's home and
receiving stolen property, a plea deal that is expected to result in a
two-year prison term when he is sentenced next week.

Hunnicutt, though, is cooperating with police to recover the stolen items,
hoping that shortens his sentence.

Hunnicutt told police Kammerer helped him steal the art.

Kammerer, 41, of West Chester, was arrested Tuesday and charged with
complicity to burglary, accused of providing Hunnicutt with a ride to and
from the home.

Police said Hunnicutt did some handyman work at Lester's home and later
returned - after getting a ride from Kammerer - to steal the lithographs and
jade figurines.

The lithographs were of original pages of some Seuss books and were
autographed by the author, Theodor Seuss Geisel.

Kammerer's father, Robert F. Kammerer, who operates the Springdale Coin and
Antique Shop, said he bought the lithographs from Hunnicutt.

"He had some pictures he wanted to sell," Robert Kammerer said Wednesday of
Hunnicutt.

"We bought them not knowing they were stolen. It was a good buy."

Robert Kammerer said he did not pay "more than $1,000" for the lithographs.

Robert Kammerer said he and his son didn't find out until Tuesday the
lithographs were stolen.

They found out, Robert Kammerer said, when police pulled over the van his
son was driving and found some of the lithographs inside. They arrested Sean
Kammerer.

That arrest came less than a week after Hunnicutt pleaded guilty before
Hamilton County Common Pleas Court Judge Robert Ruehlman.

Sean Kammerer's attorney said in court Wednesday he has "mental issues" and
is easily manipulated.

"I think he was used in this case," said his attorney, Anna Schmalz.

Neither police nor Lester returned calls Wednesday.


http://news.cincinnati.com/
